Moments

Your cosmic guide to turning forces!

Official Definition:
What is a Moment?
A moment is the turning effect produced when a force is exerted on an object. It's the 'twist' caused by a force around a fixed point.

Real-World Examples

  • A child on a see-saw
  • Turning the handle of a spanner
  • A door opening and closing
  • Using a crane or wheelbarrow
  • Using scissors or a screwdriver

The Pivot

Forces cause rotation about a fixed point. This point is called the pivot or fulcrum. The force causes either a clockwise or anticlockwise rotation.

(Refer to the diagram of a force causing rotation).

The Moment Equation

The size of a moment is defined by the equation:

moment = force × perpendicular distance from the pivot

The unit for a moment is the Newton-metre (N m).

Critical Exam Tip:
Perpendicular Forces
The distance in the equation MUST be the perpendicular distance (at 90¬∞) from the pivot to the line of action of the force. If the force isn't perpendicular, you must find its perpendicular component first!

Checkpoint Quiz 1

The Principle of Moments

For an object to be balanced and not rotate (in equilibrium), the following must be true about any chosen pivot point:

Sum of Clockwise Moments = Sum of Anticlockwise Moments
The Two Conditions
for Equilibrium

1. No resultant force: All forces are balanced.

  • Sum of upward forces = Sum of downward forces
  • Sum of leftward forces = Sum of rightward forces

2. No resultant moment: All turning effects are balanced (Principle of Moments).

Checkpoint Quiz 2

What is the Centre of Gravity?
The Centre of Gravity (C.G.) is the single point through which the entire weight of an object appears to act. For uniform objects (like a ruler), it's at the geometric centre.

How to Be Stable

An object's stability is increased by having:

  • A low centre of gravity.
  • A wide base area.

(Think of a low, wide racing car vs a tall, narrow bus).

When Does an Object Topple?

An object is stable as long as the vertical line passing through its centre of gravity (the line of action of its weight) falls within its base area.

It will topple over if this line falls outside the base area.

(Refer to the diagram of a toppling bus).

Checkpoint Quiz 3

Aim of Experiment

To determine the position of the centre of gravity of a plane lamina (a flat, thin, irregularly shaped object).

Apparatus

  • Plane lamina
  • Retort stand & clamp
  • Plumb line
  • Pencil & Ruler

Method

  1. Punch 3 holes near the outer edges of the lamina.
  2. Hang the lamina from the clamp so it swings freely.
  3. Use a plumb line aligned with the hole to show the vertical line.
  4. Mark this vertical line on the lamina.
  5. Repeat the process for the other two holes.
  6. The point where all three lines cross is the centre of gravity!
Systematic Errors
(Setup Flaws)
Parallax Error: Viewing the plumb line from an angle. Fix by viewing it straight on.

Drawing Error: Make small dots first while hanging, then connect with a ruler after.
Random Errors
(Inconsistent Actions)
Swinging: Allow lamina to settle completely before marking.

Hole Punching: Punch all holes before starting, as adding them later changes the C.G.
